## Findings

### [SEVERITY: critical] Stuck-bout sweep refunds the full preauth even when the bout already consumed model time
File: lib/bout-sweep.ts:83
Pattern: cost-margin-asymmetry
What: `sweepStuckBouts()` reconstructs the refund solely from the original `preauth` row and always credits back `abs(preauth.deltaMicro)`, with no attempt to account for turns already generated before the worker died.
Why: The normal error path in `lib/bout-execution.ts` refunds only `preauth - actualCost`; the sweep path refunds 100%. Any timeout/crash after partial generation leaks credits and underreports actual platform spend.
Fix: Persist enough progress/cost data to compute unused preauth on sweep, or restrict automatic sweep refunds to bouts proven to have consumed no model work.

### [SEVERITY: major] The new completion hook can announce “completed” for bouts that later get flipped to `error`
File: lib/bout-execution.ts:692
Pattern: WD-SH
What: `onBoutCompleted({ status: 'completed' })` fires immediately after the completion row write, but before later fallible work like `serverTrack(...)` and `settleCredits(...)`.
Why: If any of the later awaits throw, the outer catch rewrites the bout to `status='error'` and invokes the hook again with `status: 'error'`; downstream consumers can advance brackets or trigger side effects off a false completion signal first.
Fix: Move the completed hook after all remaining throwable post-write work, or make the post-write analytics/settlement paths non-throwing before the hook runs.

### [SEVERITY: major] DAL extraction turns database unavailability into a false 404 for replay pages
File: lib/bouts.ts:14
Pattern: WD-LRT
What: `getBoutById()` now returns `null` both when the bout is missing and when the shared `db` handle is unavailable, and callers like `app/b/[id]/page.tsx` treat `null` as `notFound()`.
Why: A transient database outage now becomes a real 404 response instead of a 5xx, so users and crawlers can cache “missing bout” for content that actually exists.
Fix: Split the helper into a throwing page-route version and a nullable metadata-safe version, or make `getBoutById()` throw on `!db` and let metadata generators handle that separately.

### [SEVERITY: minor] The “Redis unavailable -> in-memory fallback” limiter still pays the Redis failure cost on every request
File: lib/rate-limit.ts:37
Pattern: WD-PG
What: After the first Upstash failure, `sharedRedis` and the cached `Ratelimit` instances remain live, so every later `checkRateLimit()` still calls `distributed.limit(identifier)` before falling back.
Why: During a Redis outage, protected endpoints keep incurring the dead-network timeout path on every request, so the fallback is not actually graceful under load.
Fix: Trip a local circuit breaker on failure by clearing/disabling the Redis-backed limiter for a cooldown window before retrying.

